                                                     Amarnath: IPL will not help India 
            A STAFF REPORTER            Amarnath at the Eden on Sunday. A Telegraph picture                           
	Calcutta: Former allrounder Mohinder Amarnath feels that the Indian boards multi-million-dollar Indian Premier League (IPL) has no real future.         
	According to him, because of the IPL promising cricketers will lose interest in the domestic tournaments and the supply line will be affected.         
	The IPL is not mainstream cricket. It is more amusement than cricket, Amarnath, who was in the city on Sunday in connection with a cricket tournament, said.         
	Its a commercial venture. If somebody says he is doing it for sports, then he is wrong, he added.         
	This Twenty20 game will not help the future of Indian cricket. It will dry up the supply line The Ranji Trophy will be the worst hit, he said.         
	Talking about IPLs effect on Test cricket, Amarnath said: Test cricket is a different game and its popularity will always be there.         
	Coming down heavily on the auction of worlds top cricketers, he said: Players have been made to look like commodities in any commercial venture. They could have avoided the auction.         
	Commenting on the exclusion of former Indian captains  Sourav Ganguly and Rahul Dravid  from the ODI team, Amarnath said: I was surprised when the duo were dropped Especially Sourav He made a great comeback last time. Its unfortunate that he has to prove himself again. I feel both should be there in the ODI squad.                                                                                                                       
